glish magazine editors]]\n[[Category:The Spectator editors]]\n[[Category:Daily Telegraph journalists]]\n[[Category:The Times people]]\n[[Category:20th-century British journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British journalists]]\n[[Category:English political writers]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:20th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English writers]]\n[[Category:American magazine editors]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:People who lost United States citizenship]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Oxford Union]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ashdown House]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:English Anglicans]]\n[[Category:American Anglicans]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Converts to Anglicanism from Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:Christians from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Christians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:English people of American descent]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:People from Crouch End]]\n[[Category:People from Maida Vale]]\n[[Category:People from Uccle]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Norwalk, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Writers from Norwalk, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Politicians from New York City]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper East Side]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the European Schools]]\n", "name_user": "Diplobiont", "label": "safe", "comment": "caption style", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boris_Johnson"}
{"title_page": "Robert Wendel", "text_new": "{{for|the French steelmaker|Robert de Wendel}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Robert Wendel\n| image                     = File:Robert Wendel.jpg\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date|1951|06|21}}\n| birth_place               = [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]]\n| nationality               = American\n| alma_mater                = [[University Of Connecticut]]\n| occupation                = [[Composer]], [[conductor]], [[music publisher]]\n| years_active              = 1974\u2013present\n| awards                    = [[The American Prize]]: <br/> 2014 Judge's Special Citation,  2015 Honored Artist }}\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]] in 1951, '''Robert Wendel''' attended the [[University of Connecticut]]<ref>http://uconnmagazine.uconn.edu/smmr2010/feature4.html</ref> double majoring in chemistry and music. While at the university, Robert studied with [[Hale Smith]] and privately with [[Leroy Anderson]]. He also served as assistant conductor of both the University Of Connecticut Symphony and the New Britain Symphony. After receiving his Master of Arts degree, Robert immersed himself in musical theater in Florida for several years before he moved to New York City and became an orchestra member and stand-by conductor at [[Radio City Music Hall]] under Don Pippin, became conductor/arranger for [[Carol Channing]]<ref>http://www.nsmt.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=389&Itemid=389</ref>, and did an international tour and [[VH-1]] telecast as conductor for [[Harry Connick, Jr.]],\n\nIn 1990 while still touring with stars and shows, Robert started his own publishing and music rental library, \"Robert Wendel Music.\" His work appears on several albums for [[Telarc]], [[Naxos Records|Naxos]],<ref>http://www.naxos.com/person/Robert_Wendel/28472.htm</ref> [[ABC Classics]], and others. Live performances and broadcasts have included the [[Cincinnati Pops]], [[New York Pops]], Atlanta, Houston, Baltimore, Cleveland, St. Louis, Dallas, Seattle, Flint, National, BBC, Royal Scottish National, Tasmanian, Bochum, Toronto, Edmonton, and many other orchestras, under conductors [[Erich Kunzel]], [[Steven Reineke]], Michael Krajewski, [[David Charles Abell]], [[John Morris Russell]], [[Enrique Diemecke]], Sean O'Boyle, Carl Topilow, and many others.\n\nHis music has been featured at a memorial concert for the Challenger astronauts at The [[Kennedy Space Center]], <ref>http://www.wendelmusic.com/images/photos/Brevard.jpg</ref>  at a concert to honor the [[Tuskegee Airmen]],<ref>http://daytonperformingarts.org/content.jsp?articleId=2111</ref> on the 2006 [[National Memorial Day Concert]] to honor the opening of the [[National World War II Memorial]] telecast live nation-wide on [[PBS]],<ref>{{YouTube|id=-mZFR_e6qr0&list=UUe57yqzkY3t42JkdQ_sbkaw}}</ref> and in 2009 as part of the Abraham Lincoln tribute, and again in 2011 for Gen. Colin Powell's welcome home to our troops on the National Mall, and again in 2017 to honor all the veterans of WW2.<ref>{{YouTube|id=m7as5RdACck&t=22s}}</ref>\n\nRobert has also written for \"Cirque de la Symphonie\"<ref>http://www.timesrecordnews.com/news/2013/dec/14/dont-miss-it-cirque-de-la-symphonie/?print=1</ref> and for television.<ref>http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/2806-Walmart-Christmas-Morning-Magic</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn December 2014 Robert Wendel was awarded The American Prize Judge's Special Citation for \"Music for Use. Well Crafted, Accessible and Performance-Ready.\"<ref>http://theamericanprize.blogspot.com/2014/12/special-judges-citations-to-two.html</ref>  Robert also received The American Prize as one of five \"Honored Artists\" for 2015.<ref>http://theamericanprize.blogspot.com/2016/01/the-american-prize-announces-five.html</ref>\n\n===Works List===\n\n====Orchestral====\n*\"Fanfare For Freedom\" (1994)\n**Premiered by the [[Atlanta Symphony]]\n*\"The Tall Ships\" (1999)\n**Premiered by the [[Tasmanian Symphony Orchestra]]\n*\"Commemoration\" (2000)\n**Broadcast premiere by the [[National Symphony Orchestra]]\n*\"Parade Of The Percussionists\" (2000)\n**Premiered by the Hilo Philharmonic\n*\"Ride Of The Headless Horseman\" (2001) - from \"A Halloween Trilogy\"\n** Premiered by The [[Queensland Symphony Orchestra]]\n*\"Take Flight\" (2003)\n**Premiered by the [[Columbus Symphony Orchestra]]\n*\"The Pit And The Pendulum\" (2004) - from \"A Halloween Trilogy\"\n**Premiered by the Chicago Civic Symphony\n*\"Towers Of Light\" (2006)\n**Premiered by The Atlanta Symphony Youth Orchestra\n**Named a finalist in the first \"American Prize\" in Orchestral Composition<ref>http://theamericanprize.blogspot.com/2011/03/finalists-in-choral-orchestral.html</ref>\n*\"Trick Or Treat\" (2006) - from \"A Halloween Trilogy\"<ref>http://www.thewritehag.com/index2.php?page=Reviews</ref>\n**Premiered by the Hilton Head Orchestra\n*\"Meditation\" (2008)\n**Premiered by the University Of Wyoming Symphony\n*\"Fanfare: Welcome Home\" (2010)\n**Premiered by the Gulf Coast Symphony\n*\"Caribbean Sleigh Ride\" (2010)\n**Premiered by The [[Orlando Philharmonic Orchestra]]<ref>http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2010-11-27/entertainment/os-ppl-review-orlando-philharmonic-ho20101124_1_holiday-concert-holiday-spirits-robert-wendel</ref>\n*\"The Wolf Was Framed!\" (2011)\n**Premiered by the Cherokee Symphony, Lee Thorson conductor.\n*\"The Poltergeist Polka\" (2011)\n**Premiered by the [[Dayton Philharmonic Orchestra]]\n*\"The Nativity Bells\" (After Byrd) (2013)\n**Premiered by The [[Atlanta Symphony]]<ref>http://www.morgancountycitizen.com/the-madison-morgan-cultural-center-hosts-the-atlanta-symphony-orchestra/</ref>\n\n====Vocal====\n*\"Christmas Through Children's Eyes\" (2001)\n**Lyrics by Vince Trani\n*\"Santa Dear\" (2002)\n**Lyrics by Vince Trani and Robert Wendel\n*\"The Bells Of Christmas\" (2003)\n**Lyrics by Vince Trani\n*\"Virginia, 1861\" (2011) - For the sesquicentennial of the Civil War.\n**for S.A.T.B. choir, boys choir and orchestra from texts by Melville, and Joyce.\n*\"It Wouldn't Be Christmas Without you\" (2011)\n**Lyrics by Vince Trani\n**Premiered by the Arkansas Symphony\n*\"This Is Chanukah\" (2013)\n**Co-Premiered by The [[Philly Pops]] and The University Of Wyoming Symphony and chorus.<ref>http://articles.philly.com/2013-12-11/entertainment/45038764_1_christmas-spectacular-philly-pops-pops-festival-chorus</ref> \n**Named a finalist for the 2014 \"American Prize for Choral Composition.\" <ref>http://theamericanprize.blogspot.com</ref>\n*\"Holiday Greetings\" (2014)\n** Premiered by David Charles Abell conducting The Philly Pops, Festival Chorus, and Philadelphia Boys Choir.\n*\"We're Having A Heat Wave For Christmas\" (2019)\n** Premiered by Steve Larson conducting the Rockford Symphony (IL)\n\n\n==Discography==\n* [http://www.cdbaby.com/cd/wendelrobert ''American Reflections''] Catalog No: RWM001\n* [http://www.cdbaby.com/cd/wendelrobert2 ''Christmas Old And New''] Catalog No: RWM002\n* [http://www.amazon.com/dp/B000HIVOBY ''Christmastime Is Here''] Telarc - \"Little Bolero Boy\" and \"We Need A Little Christmas\"\n* [http://shop.abc.net.au/browse/product.asp?productid=370970 ''Soliloquy''] ABC - Catalog No:4767929 - \"Commemoration\"\n* [http://www.amazon.com/dp/B0000EI98P/?%5Fencoding=UTF8 ''Christmas Festival''] Houston Symphony Society - Catalog No: B0000EI98P - \"Christmas a la Valse!\"\n* [https://bpo.org/shop-bpo/merchandise/ \"Sounds Of The Season\"] Buffalo Philharmonic Orchestra Recordings - \"We Need A Little Christmas\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://theamericanprize.blogspot.com/2011/05/american-prize-in-compositionorchestral.html \"The American Prize\"]\n*[http://theamericanprize.blogspot.com/2016/01/the-american-prize-announces-five.html \"The American Prize\"]\n*[http://www.leroyanderson.com/links.php \"Leroy Anderson Music for hire.\"]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/user/lednew2010 Selections on YouTube]\n\n\n\n{{Persondata <!-- Metadata: see [[Wikipedia:Persondata]]. -->\n| NAME              = Wendel, Robert\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES = Bob\n| SHORT DESCRIPTION = American composer\n| DATE OF BIRTH     = 1951\n| PLACE OF BIRTH    = Bridgeport, CT\n| DATE OF DEATH     =\n| PLACE OF DEATH    =\n}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wendel, Robert}}\n[[Category:American male classical composers]]\n[[Category:American classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:University of Connecticut alumni]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Bridgeport, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Light music composers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the French steelmaker|Robert de Wendel}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:Robert Wendel.jpg|thumb|right|Robert Wendel]]\n'''Robert Wendel''' is an American composer of classical and pops music.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]] in 1951, '''Robert Wendel''' attended the [[University of Connecticut]]<ref>http://uconnmagazine.uconn.edu/smmr2010/feature4.html</ref> double majoring in chemistry and music. While at the university, Robert studied with [[Hale Smith]] and privately with [[Leroy Anderson]]. He also served as assistant conductor of both the University Of Connecticut Symphony and the New Britain Symphony. After receiving his Master of Arts degree, Robert immersed himself in musical theater in Florida for several years before he moved to New York City and became an orchestra member and stand-by conductor at [[Radio City Music Hall]] under Don Pippin, became conductor/arranger for [[Carol Channing]]<ref>http://www.nsmt.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=389&Itemid=389</ref>, and did an international tour and [[VH-1]] telecast as conductor for [[Harry Connick, Jr.]],\n\nIn 1990 while still touring with stars and shows, Robert started his own publishing and music rental library, \"Robert Wendel Music.\" His work appears on several albums for [[Telarc]], [[Naxos Records|Naxos]],<ref>http://www.naxos.com/person/Robert_Wendel/28472.htm</ref> [[ABC Classics]], and others. Live performances and broadcasts have included the [[Cincinnati Pops]], [[New York Pops]], Atlanta, Houston, Baltimore, Cleveland, St. Louis, Dallas, Seattle, Flint, National, BBC, Royal Scottish National, Tasmanian, Bochum, Toronto, Edmonton, and many other orchestras, under conductors [[Erich Kunzel]], [[Steven Reineke]], Michael Krajewski, [[David Charles Abell]], [[John Morris Russell]], [[Enrique Diemecke]], Sean O'Boyle, Carl Topilow, and many others.\n\nHis music has been featured at a memorial concert for the Challenger astronauts at The [[Kennedy Space Center]], <ref>http://www.wendelmusic.com/images/photos/Brevard.jpg</ref>  at a concert to honor the [[Tuskegee Airmen]],<ref>http://daytonperformingarts.org/content.jsp?articleId=2111</ref> on the 2006 [[National Memorial Day Concert]] to honor the opening of the [[National World War II Memorial]] telecast live nation-wide on [[PBS]],<ref>{{YouTube|id=-mZFR_e6qr0&list=UUe57yqzkY3t42JkdQ_sbkaw}}</ref> and in 2009 as part of the Abraham Lincoln tribute, and again in 2011 for Gen. Colin Powell's welcome home to our troops on the National Mall, and again in 2017 to honor all the veterans of WW2.<ref>{{YouTube|id=m7as5RdACck&t=22s}}</ref>\n\nRobert has also written for \"Cirque de la Symphonie\"<ref>http://www.timesrecordnews.com/news/2013/dec/14/dont-miss-it-cirque-de-la-symphonie/?print=1</ref> and for television.<ref>http://www.splendad.com/ads/show/2806-Walmart-Christmas-Morning-Magic</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn December 2014 Robert Wendel was awarded The American Prize Judge's Special Citation for \"Music for Use. Well Crafted, Accessible and Performance-Ready.\"<ref>http://theamericanprize.blogspot.com/2014/12/special-judges-citations-to-two.html</ref>  Robert also received The American Prize as one of five \"Honored Artists\" for 2015.<ref>http://theamericanprize.blogspot.com/2016/01/the-american-prize-announces-five.html</ref>\n\n===Works List===\n\n====Orchestral====\n*\"Fanfare For Freedom\" (1994)\n**Premiered by the [[Atlanta Symphony]]\n*\"The Tall Ships\" (1999)\n**Premiered by the [[Tasmanian Symphony Orchestra]]\n*\"Commemoration\" (2000)\n**Broadcast premiere by the [[National Symphony Orchestra]]\n*\"Parade Of The Percussionists\" (2000)\n**Premiered by the Hilo Philharmonic\n*\"Ride Of The Headless Horseman\" (2001) - from \"A Halloween Trilogy\"\n** Premiered by The [[Queensland Symphony Orchestra]]\n*\"Take Flight\" (2003)\n**Premiered by the [[Columbus Symphony Orchestra]]\n*\"The Pit And The Pendulum\" (2004) - from \"A Halloween Trilogy\"\n**Premiered by the Chicago Civic Symphony\n*\"Towers Of Light\" (2006)\n**Premiered by The Atlanta Symphony Youth Orchestra\n**Named a finalist in the first \"American Prize\" in Orchestral Composition<ref>http://theamericanprize.blogspot.com/2011/03/finalists-in-choral-orchestral.html</ref>\n*\"Trick Or Treat\" (2006) - from \"A Halloween Trilogy\"<ref>http://www.thewritehag.com/index2.php?page=Reviews</ref>\n**Premiered by the Hilton Head Orchestra\n*\"Meditation\" (2008)\n**Premiered by the University Of Wyoming Symphony\n*\"Fanfare: Welcome Home\" (2010)\n**Premiered by the Gulf Coast Symphony\n*\"Caribbean Sleigh Ride\" (2010)\n**Premiered by The [[Orlando Philharmonic Orchestra]]<ref>http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2010-11-27/entertainment/os-ppl-review-orlando-philharmonic-ho20101124_1_holiday-concert-holiday-spirits-robert-wendel</ref>\n*\"The Wolf Was Framed!\" (2011)\n**Premiered by the Cherokee Symphony, Lee Thorson conductor.\n*\"The Poltergeist Polka\" (2011)\n**Premiered by the [[Dayton Philharmonic Orchestra]]\n*\"The Nativity Bells\" (After Byrd) (2013)\n**Premiered by The [[Atlanta Symphony]]<ref>http://www.morgancountycitizen.com/the-madison-morgan-cultural-center-hosts-the-atlanta-symphony-orchestra/</ref>\n\n====Vocal====\n*\"Christmas Through Children's Eyes\" (2001)\n**Lyrics by Vince Trani\n*\"Santa Dear\" (2002)\n**Lyrics by Vince Trani and Robert Wendel\n*\"The Bells Of Christmas\" (2003)\n**Lyrics by Vince Trani\n*\"Virginia, 1861\" (2011) - For the sesquicentennial of the Civil War.\n**for S.A.T.B. choir, boys choir and orchestra from texts by Melville, and Joyce.\n*\"It Wouldn't Be Christmas Without you\" (2011)\n**Lyrics by Vince Trani\n**Premiered by the Arkansas Symphony\n*\"This Is Chanukah\" (2013)\n**Co-Premiered by The [[Philly Pops]] and The University Of Wyoming Symphony and chorus.<ref>http://articles.philly.com/2013-12-11/entertainment/45038764_1_christmas-spectacular-philly-pops-pops-festival-chorus</ref> \n**Named a finalist for the 2014 \"American Prize for Choral Composition.\" <ref>http://theamericanprize.blogspot.com</ref>\n*\"Holiday Greetings\" (2014)\n** Premiered by David Charles Abell conducting The Philly Pops, Festival Chorus, and Philadelphia Boys Choir.\n*\"We're Having A Heat Wave For Christmas\" (2019)\n** Premiered by Steve Larson conducting the Rockford Symphony (IL)\n\n\n==Discography==\n* [http://www.cdbaby.com/cd/wendelrobert ''American Reflections''] Catalog No: RWM001\n* [http://www.cdbaby.com/cd/wendelrobert2 ''Christmas Old And New''] Catalog No: RWM002\n* [http://www.amazon.com/dp/B000HIVOBY ''Christmastime Is Here''] Telarc - \"Little Bolero Boy\" and \"We Need A Little Christmas\"\n* [http://shop.abc.net.au/browse/product.asp?productid=370970 ''Soliloquy''] ABC - Catalog No:4767929 - \"Commemoration\"\n* [http://www.amazon.com/dp/B0000EI98P/?%5Fencoding=UTF8 ''Christmas Festival''] Houston Symphony Society - Catalog No: B0000EI98P - \"Christmas a la Valse!\"\n* [https://bpo.org/shop-bpo/merchandise/ \"Sounds Of The Season\"] Buffalo Philharmonic Orchestra Recordings - \"We Need A Little Christmas\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://theamericanprize.blogspot.com/2011/05/american-prize-in-compositionorchestral.html \"The American Prize\"]\n*[http://theamericanprize.blogspot.com/2016/01/the-american-prize-announces-five.html \"The American Prize\"]\n*[http://www.leroyanderson.com/links.php \"Leroy Anderson Music for hire.\"]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/user/lednew2010 Selections on YouTube]\n\n\n\n{{Persondata <!-- Metadata: see [[Wikipedia:Persondata]]. -->\n| NAME              = Wendel, Robert\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES = Bob\n| SHORT DESCRIPTION = American composer\n| DATE OF BIRTH     = 1951\n| PLACE OF BIRTH    = Bridgeport, CT\n| DATE OF DEATH     =\n| PLACE OF DEATH    =\n}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wendel, Robert}}\n[[Category:American male classical composers]]\n[[Category:American classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:University of Connecticut alumni]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Bridgeport, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Light music composers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Bobwen", "label": "safe", "comment": "added Infobox person", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Wendel"}
{"title_page": "Jonathan Sri", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n|honorific_prefix = [[City of Brisbane|Councillor]]\n|name             = Jonathan Sri\n|honorific-suffix =  \n|image            = File:Jonathan_Sri.jpg\n|caption          =  \n|office           = Member of the [[City of Brisbane|Brisbane City Council]]\n|term_start       = 12 April 2016 \n|term_end         =  \n|predecessor      = [[The Gabba Ward#Councillors for the Gabba Ward|Helen Abrahams]]\n|constituency     = [[The Gabba Ward]]\n|birth_name       =  \n|birth_date       =  \n|birth_place      = [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], Australia\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Queensland Greens]]\n|spouse           = \n|children         = \n|residence        =  \n|alma_mater       = [[University of Queensland]] <br /> <small>([[Bachelor of Laws|LLB]], [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])</small>\n}}\n\n'''Cr Jonathan Sri''' is a [[Queensland Greens]] councillor for the [[City of Brisbane|Brisbane City Council]], representing [[The Gabba Ward]].<ref name=\"gabbaward\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbane.qld.gov.au/about-council/governance-strategy/councillors-wards/gabba-ward|title=The Gabba Ward|date=2016-03-09|website=www.brisbane.qld.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\n\n=== 2015 State Election ===\nCr Sri stood as the Greens candidate for [[Electoral district of South Brisbane|South Brisbane]] at the [[2015 Queensland state election]], where he received 21.8% of the primary vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/qld-election-2015/guide/sbri/|title=South Brisbane - Queensland Election 2015 - Qld Election 2015 (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref> He was defeated by current Labor MP [[Jackie Trad]], and placed third after the [[Liberal National Party of Queensland|Liberal National Party]].\n\n=== 2016 Brisbane City Council Election ===\nCr Sri stood as a candidate for The Gabba Ward at the [[2016 Brisbane City Council election]], held on 19 March, where he received 31.7% of the primary vote.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/elections/brisbane-city-council-2016/wards/tgab/|title=The Gabba - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref> Preferences from the [[Australian Labor Party (Queensland Branch)|Labor]] candidate, Nicole Lessio, gave Cr Sri 55% of the [[two-party-preferred vote]], and he declared victory on 23 March after receiving a [[Concession (politics)|concession call]] from Lessio.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-03-23/greens-win-first-queensland-council-seat-gabba-sri/7270758|title=Greens win first Queensland local government seat|date=2016-03-23|work=ABC News|access-date=2017-10-24|language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2016/mar/23/queensland-elects-its-first-greens-councillor-jonathan-sri|title=Queensland elects its first Greens councillor, Jonathan Sri|last=Robertson|first=Joshua|date=2016-03-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-10-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n\nHe was sworn in on 12 April 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/four-new-brisbane-councillors-representing-three-parties-with-one-aim-20160412-go4snj.html|title=Four new Brisbane councillors, representing three parties, with one aim|last=Atfield|first=Cameron|date=2016-04-12|website=Brisbane Times|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref> becoming the first Greens councillor anywhere in [[Queensland]], and the first of [[Sri Lankan Australians|Sri Lankan]] [[Tamil Australians|Tamil]] heritage.<ref name=\"brisbanetimes\" />\n\n=== Election Commitments ===\nAt the 2016 election, Cr Sri's ideas included:\n\n* Hold a plebiscite with local residents to determine if various neighbourhood plans in the Gabba Ward should be scrapped.\n* Introduce an online voting system for residents to inform him of issues.\n* Fix Stanley Street and Annerley Road intersection.\n* Install pedestrian crossings along Vulture Street, Stanley Street and Montague Road.\n* Make public transport cheaper.\n* Establish a network of home-owners with spare bedrooms to accommodate people who cannot find affordable housing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://westender.com.au/draft-jonathan-sri-greens-candidate-for-the-gabba-ward/|title=Jonathan Sri - Greens Candidate for The Gabba Ward #bccvotes|date=2016-01-28|website=Westender - West End 4101|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Dornoch Terrace ===\nCr Sri believes that the future of transport in the Gabba Ward is \"cycling, buses, trains and feet\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://westender.com.au/know-candidate-jonathan-sri-qldvotes2015/|title=Know your Candidate - Jonathan Sri - #QLDVOTES2015|date=2015-01-18|website=Westender - West End 4101|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Cr Sri specifically requested the Brisbane City Council redesign Dornoch Terrace to improve safety for cyclists<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://catholicleader.com.au/news/access-woes-for-st-francis-hall-south-brisbane-with-newly-proposed-cyclist-project|title=West End parishioners outraged at council plan to remove car parks across from church|last=Bowling|first=Mark|date=2019-10-30|website=The Catholic Leader|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>. The changes brought in by the LNP council prior to public consultation being thoroughly carried out included the elimination of 115 car parking spaces. Most of the changes were welcomed by Cr Sri.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/big-changes-planned-for-brisbane-cycling-black-spot-20191003-p52xe8.html|title=Big changes planned for Brisbane cycling black spot|last=Moore|first=Tony|date=2019-10-03|website=Brisbane Times|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> \n\nNo further plans have been put forward by Brisbane City Council. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=CMWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.couriermail.com.au%2Fnews%2Fqueensland%2Fbrisbane-city-council-scraps-plans-to-replace-115-car-parks-with-bike-lanes-on-highgate-hill-street%2Fnews-story%2F2b6593bb85ecb2c00086cf2bc5dd2584&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=d273f28f6f6888fc235fe5333487221e-1576662086|title=Couriermail.com.au {{!}} Subscribe to The Courier Mail for exclusive stories|website=www.couriermail.com.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n== Political Ideology ==\nCr Sri is a self-declared [[Communitarianism|anarcho-communitarian]]. He is openly supportive of \"public disobedience\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jonathansri.com/disruptiveprotest|title=Can Roadblocks Help Change the Political Climate?|last=Jul 23|first=About the author Jonathan Sri Facebook Twitter Website Published|last2=2019|website=Jonathan Sri|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref> and has posted information to assist followers in avoiding being fined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jonathansri.com/peacefulassembly|title=Peaceful Assembly Act - Organising protests without getting fined|last=Sep 28|first=About the author Jonathan Sri Published|last2=2018|website=Jonathan Sri|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n[[File:Facebook Post by Jonathan Sri.png|alt=For the record, I'm more of an anarcho-communitarian than a socialist or communist.|thumb|Facebook Post by Jonathan Sri on political ideology]]\n[[File:Rebellion Day Brisbane (48470290381).jpg|alt=Sri speaking to a crowd outside Queens Wharf, Brisbane|thumb|Sri at Rebellion Day, Brisbane]]\nCr Sri also regularly discusses flaws in the current political system and advocates for its end.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jonathansri.com/stayingradical|title=Changing the system or is it changing us?|last=Mar 12|first=About the author Jonathan Sri Facebook Twitter Website Published|last2=2019|website=Jonathan Sri|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n=== Illegal sharehouse ===\nWhen elected in 2016, Cr Sri was living in an illegal sharehouse with seven other adults. The LNP-dominated Brisbane City Council opted not to instigate any action.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/greens-councillor-jonathan-sri-defends-his-illegal-share-house-20160510-goqjxj.html|title=Greens councillor Jonathan Sri defends his illegal share house|last=Atfield|first=Cameron|date=2016-05-10|website=Brisbane Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref> \n\n=== Protest against development ===\nIn 2016, Cr Sri organised human barricades and protests against the controversial West Village development in West End.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/questnews/councillor-jonathan-sri-leads-protest-at-controversial-west-village-development/news-story/49cae5c84bb4f662eb7175bff09b9a73|title=West Village protest shut down|date=2016-11-09|website=www.couriermail.com.au|language=en|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref> The development still went ahead.\n\n=== Altercations with real estate agents ===\nCr Sri has named and shamed real estate agents he believes were exploiting tenants to draw attention to the need to reform Queensland tenancy laws.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sri |first1=Jonathan |title=Cr |url=https://www.jonathansri.com/shamingbadagents |website=Why I\u2019ve Decided to Name and Shame Real Estate Agents |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref> In October 2018, a local real estate agent accused Sri of harassing him, and the complaint was referred to a councillor conduct review panel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-10-31/brisbane-councillor-jonathan-sri-under-investigation/10448482|title=Brisbane councillor investigated over 'harassment, stalking' claims by real estate agent|last=Swanston|first=Tim|date=2018-10-31|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Criticism of the Queensland Police ===\nCr Sri has called the Queensland Police Service a \"violent and racist\" organisation. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/brisbane-council-condemns-jonathan-sri-s-comments-on-police-violence-20191015-p530v2.html|title=Brisbane council condemns Jonathan Sri's comments on police violence|last=Stone|first=Lucy|date=2019-10-15|website=Brisbane Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Hoax voicemail ===\nIn October 2019, Cr Sri was fined $1,300 for \"inappropriate conduct\" by the Councillor Conduct Review Panel, after \"posing as a concerned resident in a hoax voicemail\" left for state MP [[Jennifer Howard (Australian politician)|Jennifer Howard]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-10-18/greens-councillor-jonathan-sri-says-sorry-fake-voice-message/11617080|title=Greens councillor Jonathan Sri apologises over fake voicemail|publisher=ABC News|date=18 October 2019|access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Protests with Extinction Rebellion ===\nIn August 2019 Cr Sri led a peaceful march through Brisbane's CBD to protest a lack of action on climate change and the Government's attempt to suppress the right to peaceful assembly, which was attended by concerned citizens and members of various climate change advocacy groups (e.g., [[Extinction Rebellion]], Grey Power Climate Protectors). \n\nCr Sri had previously tried to negotiate with council to hold the march in the Queen Street Mall so it would not block traffic, but Councillor Shrinner of the Brisbane City Council refused that option and subsequently initiated legal action in an attempt to prevent the protest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-28/queensland-protest-action-brisbane-cbd/11453104|title='Protesting is not an illegal activity': Brisbane Greens councillor leads CBD march|date=2019-08-28|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n\nCr Sri has allowed local branches of [[Extinction Rebellion]] to hold their meetings in his Ward office<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/greens-councillor-targeted-on-social-media-over-climate-activist-support-20190731-p52ckp.html|title= Greens councillor targeted on social media over climate activist support|website=Brisbane Times|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30|date= 31 July 2019}}</ref>.\n\n== Education ==\nCr Sri has a Bachelor of Laws (Hons) and Bachelor of Arts with majors in Journalism and Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies from The [[University of Queensland]]. He has previously worked in corporate law and community organising. Prior to being elected he was a musician and beat poet. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://greens.org.au/qld/person/jonathan-sri|title=Jonathan Sri, Councillor for the Gabba Ward|website=The Australian Greens|language=en|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==\nCr Sri lives on a houseboat moored in the Brisbane River with his partner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.domain.com.au/news/brisbane-councillor-jonathan-sri-lives-on-a-houseboat-so-he-can-donate-half-his-pay-20171203-gzse1x/|title=Brisbane councillor Jonathan Sri lives on a houseboat so he can donate half his pay|last=Malo|first=Jim|website=Domain|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n\nHe is a saxophonist and vocalist with Brisbane band [[The Mouldy Lovers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/queensland-government/brisbane-greens-councillor-jonathan-sri-on-japanese-jaunt-with-his-band/news-story/a19de8b14754b75146a23754f239a6eb|title=Brisbane Greens councillor Jonathan Sri on Japanese jaunt with his band|last=Snowdon|first=Tom|date=2017-08-13|website=Courier Mail|language=en-AU|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref> He is known for his [[spoken word]] performances.<ref name=\"brisbanetimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/sri-lays-down-his-roots-in-council-with-a-rap-20160426-gofl83.html |title=Sri lays down his roots in council with a rap |work=Brisbane Times |last=Cooper |first=Nathanael |date=27 April 2016 |accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sri, Jonathan}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Brisbane]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brisbane]]\n[[Category:Australian Greens politicians]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Sri Lankan Tamil descent]]\n[[Category:Queensland local government politicians]]\n[[Category:Extinction Rebellion]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n|honorific_prefix = [[City of Brisbane|Councillor]]\n|name             = Jonathan Sri\n|honorific-suffix =  \n|image            = File:Jonathan_Sri.jpg\n|caption          =  \n|office           = Member of the [[City of Brisbane|Brisbane City Council]]\n|term_start       = 12 April 2016 \n|term_end         =  \n|predecessor      = [[The Gabba Ward#Councillors for the Gabba Ward|Helen Abrahams]]\n|constituency     = [[The Gabba Ward]]\n|birth_name       =  \n|birth_date       =  \n|birth_place      = [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], Australia\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Queensland Greens]]\n|spouse           = \n|children         = \n|residence        =  \n|alma_mater       = [[University of Queensland]] <br /> <small>([[Bachelor of Laws|LLB]], [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])</small>\n}}\n\n'''Jonathan Sri''' is a [[Queensland Greens]] councillor for the [[City of Brisbane|Brisbane City Council]], representing [[The Gabba Ward]].<ref name=\"gabbaward\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbane.qld.gov.au/about-council/governance-strategy/councillors-wards/gabba-ward|title=The Gabba Ward|date=2016-03-09|website=www.brisbane.qld.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\n\n=== 2015 State Election ===\nSri stood as the Greens candidate for [[Electoral district of South Brisbane|South Brisbane]] at the [[2015 Queensland state election]], where he received 21.8% of the primary vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/qld-election-2015/guide/sbri/|title=South Brisbane - Queensland Election 2015 - Qld Election 2015 (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref> He was defeated by current Labor MP [[Jackie Trad]], and placed third after the [[Liberal National Party of Queensland|Liberal National Party]].\n\n=== 2016 Brisbane City Council Election ===\nSri stood as a candidate for The Gabba Ward at the [[2016 Brisbane City Council election]], held on 19 March, where he received 31.7% of the primary vote.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/elections/brisbane-city-council-2016/wards/tgab/|title=The Gabba - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref> Preferences from the [[Australian Labor Party (Queensland Branch)|Labor]] candidate, Nicole Lessio, gave Sri 55% of the [[two-party-preferred vote]], and he declared victory on 23 March after receiving a [[Concession (politics)|concession call]] from Lessio.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-03-23/greens-win-first-queensland-council-seat-gabba-sri/7270758|title=Greens win first Queensland local government seat|date=2016-03-23|work=ABC News|access-date=2017-10-24|language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2016/mar/23/queensland-elects-its-first-greens-councillor-jonathan-sri|title=Queensland elects its first Greens councillor, Jonathan Sri|last=Robertson|first=Joshua|date=2016-03-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-10-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n\nHe was sworn in on 12 April 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/four-new-brisbane-councillors-representing-three-parties-with-one-aim-20160412-go4snj.html|title=Four new Brisbane councillors, representing three parties, with one aim|last=Atfield|first=Cameron|date=2016-04-12|website=Brisbane Times|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref> becoming the first Greens councillor anywhere in [[Queensland]], and the first of [[Sri Lankan Australians|Sri Lankan]] [[Tamil Australians|Tamil]] heritage.<ref name=\"brisbanetimes\" />\n\n=== Election Commitments ===\nAt the 2016 election, Sri's ideas included:\n\n* Hold a plebiscite with local residents to determine if various neighbourhood plans in the Gabba Ward should be scrapped.\n* Introduce an online voting system for residents to inform him of issues.\n* Fix Stanley Street and Annerley Road intersection.\n* Install pedestrian crossings along Vulture Street, Stanley Street and Montague Road.\n* Make public transport cheaper.\n* Establish a network of home-owners with spare bedrooms to accommodate people who cannot find affordable housing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://westender.com.au/draft-jonathan-sri-greens-candidate-for-the-gabba-ward/|title=Jonathan Sri - Greens Candidate for The Gabba Ward #bccvotes|date=2016-01-28|website=Westender - West End 4101|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Dornoch Terrace ===\nSri believes that the future of transport in the Gabba Ward is \"cycling, buses, trains and feet\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://westender.com.au/know-candidate-jonathan-sri-qldvotes2015/|title=Know your Candidate - Jonathan Sri - #QLDVOTES2015|date=2015-01-18|website=Westender - West End 4101|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Sri specifically requested the Brisbane City Council redesign Dornoch Terrace to improve safety for cyclists<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://catholicleader.com.au/news/access-woes-for-st-francis-hall-south-brisbane-with-newly-proposed-cyclist-project|title=West End parishioners outraged at council plan to remove car parks across from church|last=Bowling|first=Mark|date=2019-10-30|website=The Catholic Leader|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>. The changes brought in by the LNP council prior to public consultation being thoroughly carried out included the elimination of 115 car parking spaces. Most of the changes were welcomed by Sri.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/big-changes-planned-for-brisbane-cycling-black-spot-20191003-p52xe8.html|title=Big changes planned for Brisbane cycling black spot|last=Moore|first=Tony|date=2019-10-03|website=Brisbane Times|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> \n\nNo further plans have been put forward by Brisbane City Council. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=CMWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.couriermail.com.au%2Fnews%2Fqueensland%2Fbrisbane-city-council-scraps-plans-to-replace-115-car-parks-with-bike-lanes-on-highgate-hill-street%2Fnews-story%2F2b6593bb85ecb2c00086cf2bc5dd2584&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=d273f28f6f6888fc235fe5333487221e-1576662086|title=Couriermail.com.au {{!}} Subscribe to The Courier Mail for exclusive stories|website=www.couriermail.com.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n== Political Ideology ==\nSri is a self-declared [[Communitarianism|anarcho-communitarian]]. He is openly supportive of \"public disobedience\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jonathansri.com/disruptiveprotest|title=Can Roadblocks Help Change the Political Climate?|last=Jul 23|first=About the author Jonathan Sri Facebook Twitter Website Published|last2=2019|website=Jonathan Sri|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref> and has posted information to assist followers in avoiding being fined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jonathansri.com/peacefulassembly|title=Peaceful Assembly Act - Organising protests without getting fined|last=Sep 28|first=About the author Jonathan Sri Published|last2=2018|website=Jonathan Sri|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n[[File:Facebook Post by Jonathan Sri.png|alt=For the record, I'm more of an anarcho-communitarian than a socialist or communist.|thumb|Facebook Post by Jonathan Sri on political ideology]]\n[[File:Rebellion Day Brisbane (48470290381).jpg|alt=Sri speaking to a crowd outside Queens Wharf, Brisbane|thumb|Sri at Rebellion Day, Brisbane]]\nSri also regularly discusses flaws in the current political system and advocates for its end.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jonathansri.com/stayingradical|title=Changing the system or is it changing us?|last=Mar 12|first=About the author Jonathan Sri Facebook Twitter Website Published|last2=2019|website=Jonathan Sri|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n=== Illegal sharehouse ===\nWhen elected in 2016, Sri was living in an illegal sharehouse with seven other adults. The LNP-dominated Brisbane City Council opted not to instigate any action.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/greens-councillor-jonathan-sri-defends-his-illegal-share-house-20160510-goqjxj.html|title=Greens councillor Jonathan Sri defends his illegal share house|last=Atfield|first=Cameron|date=2016-05-10|website=Brisbane Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref> \n\n=== Protest against development ===\nIn 2016 he organised human barricades and protests against the controversial West Village development in West End.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/questnews/councillor-jonathan-sri-leads-protest-at-controversial-west-village-development/news-story/49cae5c84bb4f662eb7175bff09b9a73|title=West Village protest shut down|date=2016-11-09|website=www.couriermail.com.au|language=en|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref> The development still went ahead.\n\n=== Altercations with real estate agents ===\nSri has named and shamed real estate agents he believes were exploiting tenants to draw attention to the need to reform Queensland tenancy laws.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sri |first1=Jonathan |title=Cr |url=https://www.jonathansri.com/shamingbadagents |website=Why I\u2019ve Decided to Name and Shame Real Estate Agents |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref> In October 2018, a local real estate agent accused Sri of harassing him, and the complaint was referred to a councillor conduct review panel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-10-31/brisbane-councillor-jonathan-sri-under-investigation/10448482|title=Brisbane councillor investigated over 'harassment, stalking' claims by real estate agent|last=Swanston|first=Tim|date=2018-10-31|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Criticism of the Queensland Police ===\nHe has called the Queensland Police Service a \"violent and racist\" organisation. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/brisbane-council-condemns-jonathan-sri-s-comments-on-police-violence-20191015-p530v2.html|title=Brisbane council condemns Jonathan Sri's comments on police violence|last=Stone|first=Lucy|date=2019-10-15|website=Brisbane Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Hoax voicemail ===\nIn October 2019, Sri was fined $1,300 for \"inappropriate conduct\" by the Councillor Conduct Review Panel, after \"posing as a concerned resident in a hoax voicemail\" left for state MP [[Jennifer Howard (Australian politician)|Jennifer Howard]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-10-18/greens-councillor-jonathan-sri-says-sorry-fake-voice-message/11617080|title=Greens councillor Jonathan Sri apologises over fake voicemail|publisher=ABC News|date=18 October 2019|access-date=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Protests with Extinction Rebellion ===\nIn August 2019 Sri led a peaceful march through Brisbane's CBD to protest a lack of action on climate change and the Government's attempt to suppress the right to peaceful assembly, which was attended by concerned citizens and members of various climate change advocacy groups (e.g., [[Extinction Rebellion]], Grey Power Climate Protectors). \n\nSri had previously tried to negotiate with council to hold the march in the Queen Street Mall so it would not block traffic, but Councillor Shrinner of the Brisbane City Council refused that option and subsequently initiated legal action in an attempt to prevent the protest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-28/queensland-protest-action-brisbane-cbd/11453104|title='Protesting is not an illegal activity': Brisbane Greens councillor leads CBD march|date=2019-08-28|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n\nSri has allowed local branches of [[Extinction Rebellion]] to hold their meetings in his Ward office<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/greens-councillor-targeted-on-social-media-over-climate-activist-support-20190731-p52ckp.html|title= Greens councillor targeted on social media over climate activist support|website=Brisbane Times|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30|date= 31 July 2019}}</ref>.\n\n== Education ==\nSri has a Bachelor of Laws (Hons) and Bachelor of Arts with majors in Journalism and Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies from The [[University of Queensland]]. He has previously worked in corporate law and community organising. Prior to being elected he was a musician and beat poet. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://greens.org.au/qld/person/jonathan-sri|title=Jonathan Sri, Councillor for the Gabba Ward|website=The Australian Greens|language=en|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==\nSri lives on a houseboat moored in the Brisbane River with his partner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.domain.com.au/news/brisbane-councillor-jonathan-sri-lives-on-a-houseboat-so-he-can-donate-half-his-pay-20171203-gzse1x/|title=Brisbane councillor Jonathan Sri lives on a houseboat so he can donate half his pay|last=Malo|first=Jim|website=Domain|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n\nHe is a saxophonist and vocalist with Brisbane band [[The Mouldy Lovers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/queensland-government/brisbane-greens-councillor-jonathan-sri-on-japanese-jaunt-with-his-band/news-story/a19de8b14754b75146a23754f239a6eb|title=Brisbane Greens councillor Jonathan Sri on Japanese jaunt with his band|last=Snowdon|first=Tom|date=2017-08-13|website=Courier Mail|language=en-AU|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref> He is known for his [[spoken word]] performances.<ref name=\"brisbanetimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/sri-lays-down-his-roots-in-council-with-a-rap-20160426-gofl83.html |title=Sri lays down his roots in council with a rap |work=Brisbane Times |last=Cooper |first=Nathanael |date=27 April 2016 |accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sri, Jonathan}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Brisbane]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brisbane]]\n[[Category:Australian Greens politicians]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Sri Lankan Tamil descent]]\n[[Category:Queensland local government politicians]]\n[[Category:Extinction Rebellion]]\n", "name_user": "Don Alfonso de Colombo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added correct prefix before surname.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonathan_Sri"}
